\section{Implementation route via the Albanese framework}

The three results above are formalised through the Albanese framework of Chapter~\ref{chap:Jacobian}. In the absence of Mathlib's Pic-scheme machinery, the Jacobian is defined as an Albanese object of $(C, P)$ (Theorem~\ref{thm:nonempty_jacobianWitness}); the universal-property data $(\iota_P, \text{factorisation})$ is then carried by the Albanese predicate (Definition~\ref{def:IsAlbanese}) and projects directly into the three results of this chapter. Existence of an Albanese object is the single remaining mathematical hypothesis pending the formalisation of either Pic-scheme representability or symmetric-power quotients in Mathlib.

The classical proof via line bundles --- using the universal property of $\Pic^0_{C/k}$, dual abelian varieties, and the rigidity theorem of Mumford \S4 --- gives the same conclusion but requires more Mathlib infrastructure (dual abelian varieties, biduality, generation of $\Jac(C)$ by the image of $\alpha_P$, the rigidity theorem). The Albanese-framework route used here is mathematically equivalent and avoids all of these obstructions.
